rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Iestyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Justin</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Rhydd ap Iestyn was born in Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Lord of GLAMORGAN Iestyn ap GWRGAST II. He married Mrs. Rhys ap Ifor about 1149, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1129–Female":"1129–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1155–1210":"1155–1210","1030–1093":"1030–1093","1129":"1129","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","Abt 1149":"umbes 1149","1030":"1030","about 1155":"umbes 1155","1160":"1160","1093":"1093","ABT 1160":"umbes 1160","Trefnant, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Mongomery,Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cantref 